# React to Laravel Blade + Livewire 4 (Single-File Components) Conversion Guide

## Overview

This guide covers converting React function components to Laravel Blade templates with **Livewire 4 single-file components** — the native view-first format where an anonymous PHP class and Blade markup live in one `.blade.php` file. This is the default and recommended approach in Livewire 4, replacing the older Volt functional API.

Each single-file component uses an anonymous class extending `Livewire\Component` at the top, followed by the Blade template, with optional scoped `<style>` and `<script>` blocks.

## Tech Stack

- **Laravel**: 12.x
- **Livewire**: 4.x (native single-file components)
- **Alpine.js**: 3.x (client-only interactions)
- **Tailwind CSS**: 4.x

> **Note on Volt**: The Volt functional API (`state()`, `computed()`, `mount()` as free functions) still works but is superseded by Livewire 4's built-in single-file format. New projects should use the native format shown in this guide.

---

## File Structure

### React (Before)

```
src/
├── components/
│   ├── Counter.jsx
│   ├── UserCard.jsx
│   └── SearchBar.jsx
├── pages/
│   ├── Home.jsx
│   └── Profile.jsx
└── App.jsx
```

### Laravel Blade + Livewire 4 (After)

```
resources/views/
├── components/
│   ├── ⚡counter.blade.php
│   ├── ⚡user-card.blade.php
│   ├── ⚡search-bar.blade.php
│   └── layouts/
│       └── app.blade.php
├── pages/
│   ├── ⚡home.blade.php
│   └── ⚡profile.blade.php
└── partials/
```

> The `⚡` prefix marks Livewire single-file components, making them instantly recognizable in the file tree. Standard Blade components (no server state) remain without the prefix.

---

## Component Conversion Patterns

### 1. Basic Function Component → Livewire Single-File Component

**React:**

```jsx
function Counter() {
    const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

    return (
        <div>
            <p>Count: {count}</p>
            <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Increment</button>
        </div>
    );
}
```

**Livewire 4 Single-File Component:**

```php
<?php // resources/views/components/⚡counter.blade.php
use Livewire\Component;

new class extends Component {
    public int $count = 0;

    public function increment(): void
    {
        $this->count++;
    }
};
?>

<div>
    <p>Count: {{ $count }}</p>
    <button wire:click="increment">Increment</button>
</div>
```

> The anonymous class extends `Component` directly. Public properties are your state, and public methods are your actions. No extra package needed.

---

### 2. Props → Public Properties via `mount()`

**React:**

```jsx
function UserCard({ name, email }) {
    return (
        <div>
            <h2>{name}</h2>
            <p>{email}</p>
        </div>
    );
}
```

**Livewire 4 Single-File Component:**

```php
<?php // resources/views/components/⚡user-card.blade.php
use Livewire\Component;

new class extends Component {
    public string $name = '';
    public string $email = '';

    // mount() receives props passed from the parent
    public function mount(string $name, string $email): void
    {
        $this->name = $name;
        $this->email = $email;
    }
};
?>

<div>
    <h2>{{ $name }}</h2>
    <p>{{ $email }}</p>
</div>
```

**Blade component for pure display (no server state needed):**

```php
{{-- resources/views/components/user-card.blade.php (no ⚡ prefix — plain Blade) --}}
@props(['name', 'email'])

<div>
    <h2>{{ $name }}</h2>
    <p>{{ $email }}</p>
</div>
```

```blade
{{-- Usage --}}
<x-user-card name="John" email="john@example.com" />
```

---

### 3. Component with Layout

**React:**

```jsx
function HomePage() {
    return (
        <Layout>
            <main>Home content</main>
        </Layout>
    );
}
```

**Livewire 4 (via `Route::livewire` and config):**

Layouts are configured in `config/livewire.php` using the `component_layout` key and the `layouts::` namespace:

```php
// config/livewire.php
'component_layout' => 'layouts::app',
```

The page component itself only contains its own content:

```php
<?php // resources/views/pages/⚡home.blade.php
use Livewire\Component;

new class extends Component {
    //
};
?>

<main>Home content</main>
```

You can also override the layout per-component using the `#[Layout]` attribute:

```php
<?php
use Livewire\Attributes\Layout;
use Livewire\Component;

#[Layout('layouts::admin')]
new class extends Component {
    //
};
?>
```

