## Routing & Navigation

### React Router → Laravel Web Routes

**React:**

```jsx
<Route path="/profile/:id" element={<ProfilePage />} />
```

**Livewire 4 `routes/web.php` — using `Route::livewire()` (preferred):**

```php
// Basic route — resolves to a Livewire component by dot-notation path
Route::livewire('dashboard', 'front.dashboard')->name('dashboard');

// Route with parameters
Route::livewire('/profile/{id}', 'pages.profile')->name('profile.show');

// With middleware
Route::livewire('/settings', 'account.settings')
    ->middleware(['auth', 'verified'])
    ->name('settings');

// Using namespaces (pages:: resolves to a configured component directory)
Route::livewire('/admin', 'pages::admin-dashboard')->name('admin.dashboard');

// Grouping routes with shared middleware
Route::middleware(['auth'])->group(function () {
    Route::livewire('dashboard', 'front.dashboard')->name('dashboard');
    Route::livewire('/orders', 'front.orders')->name('orders');
    Route::livewire('/orders/{id}', 'front.order-detail')->name('orders.show');
});
```

The second argument is a dot-notation path to the component's Blade file. For example, `'front.dashboard'` resolves to `resources/views/livewire/front/⚡dashboard.blade.php`.

**Class-based routing (still works):**

```php
use App\Livewire\Pages\Profile;

Route::get('/profile/{id}', Profile::class)->name('profile.show');
```

> **Livewire 4 namespaces**: `pages::` resolves to page components, `layouts::` resolves to layouts. You can also define custom namespaces in `config/livewire.php` under `component_namespaces` for modular apps.

### Route Params in the Component

```php
<?php
use Livewire\Component;

new class extends Component {
    public ?int $userId = null;
    public ?array $user = null;

    public function mount(int $id): void
    {
        $this->userId = $id;
        $this->user = \App\Models\User::findOrFail($id)->toArray();
    }
};
?>
```

