## Livewire 4 New Features

### Islands — Independent Rendering Regions

Islands let you wrap expensive sections of a component so they render independently, without re-rendering the entire page. This is similar to React's `<Suspense>` and lazy loading patterns.

**React (Suspense + lazy):**

```jsx
<Suspense fallback={<Spinner />}>
    <ExpensiveChart data={data} />
</Suspense>
```

**Livewire 4 Islands:**

```blade
{{-- Basic island: only this section re-renders on its own --}}
@island
    <livewire:expensive-chart :data="$data" />
@endisland

{{-- Lazy island: loads after initial page render (intersection observer) --}}
@island(lazy: true)
    <livewire:revenue-dashboard />
    @placeholder
        <div class="animate-pulse h-64 bg-gray-200 rounded"></div>
    @endplaceholder
@endisland

{{-- Deferred island: loads immediately after page render --}}
@island(defer: true)
    <livewire:notifications-panel />
@endisland

{{-- Named island: trigger updates from elsewhere with wire:island --}}
@island(name: 'cart-total')
    <livewire:cart-summary />
@endisland

<button wire:island="cart-total" wire:click="addToCart">Add to Cart</button>
```

> Islands dramatically improve performance. In benchmarks, a page rendering 29,000 Blade components dropped from 1.6 seconds to 131 milliseconds.

---

### Scoped Styles & Scripts

Component CSS and JavaScript now live directly inside the single-file component. They are automatically scoped and served as native cached files.

**React (CSS-in-JS or module CSS):**

```jsx
import styles from './Counter.module.css';

function Counter() {
    return <div className={styles.wrapper}>...</div>;
}
```

**Livewire 4 (scoped in the same file):**

```php
<?php // resources/views/components/⚡counter.blade.php
use Livewire\Component;

new class extends Component {
    public int $count = 0;

    public function increment(): void
    {
        $this->count++;
    }
};
?>

<div class="counter-wrapper">
    <p>{{ $count }}</p>
    <button wire:click="increment">+</button>
</div>

<style>
.counter-wrapper {
    padding: 1rem;
    border: 2px solid #3b82f6;
    border-radius: 0.5rem;
}
</style>

<script>
document.addEventListener('livewire:init', () => {
    console.log('Counter component loaded');
});
</script>
```

> Styles are scoped to the component automatically — no class name collisions.

---

### Loading States — `data-loading` Attribute

Livewire 4 automatically adds a `data-loading` attribute to any element that triggers a network request, replacing complex `wire:loading` configurations.

**React (loading state pattern):**

```jsx
const [saving, setSaving] = useState(false);

async function handleSave() {
    setSaving(true);
    await save();
    setSaving(false);
}

return (
    <button onClick={handleSave} disabled={saving} className={saving ? 'opacity-50' : ''}>
        {saving ? 'Saving...' : 'Save'}
    </button>
);
```

**Livewire 4 (zero-JS loading states with Tailwind):**

```blade
{{-- Automatic opacity change during request --}}
<button wire:click="save" class="data-loading:opacity-50">
    Save Changes
</button>

{{-- Show a spinner only during loading --}}
<svg class="not-data-loading:hidden animate-spin h-5 w-5">...</svg>

{{-- Style children, parents, and siblings --}}
<div class="has-data-loading:bg-gray-100">
    <button wire:click="save">Save</button>
</div>
```

> `wire:loading` still works, but `data-loading` is the simpler approach using Tailwind variants: `data-loading:`, `not-data-loading:`, `in-data-loading:`, `has-data-loading:`, `peer-data-loading:`.

---

### Slots — Livewire Components Accept Slots

Livewire components now accept slots just like Blade components, bridging the gap between the two.

**React (children prop):**

```jsx
function Card({ title, children }) {
    return (
        <div className="card">
            <h2>{title}</h2>
            <div>{children}</div>
        </div>
    );
}

<Card title="Welcome">
    <p>Hello world</p>
</Card>
```

**Livewire 4 (slots):**

```php
<?php // resources/views/components/⚡card.blade.php
use Livewire\Component;

new class extends Component {
    public string $title = '';
};
?>

<div class="card">
    <h2>{{ $title }}</h2>
    <div>{{ $slot }}</div>
</div>
```

```blade
{{-- Usage --}}
<livewire:card title="Welcome">
    <p>Hello world</p>
</livewire:card>
```

---

### `wire:ref` — Targeting Child Components

`wire:ref` lets you reference and interact with child components directly, similar to React's `useRef` for component instances.

**React:**

```jsx
const formRef = useRef();
// formRef.current.reset();
```

**Livewire 4:**

```blade
<livewire:contact-form wire:ref="contactForm" />
<button wire:click="$refs.contactForm.resetForm()">Reset Form</button>
```

---

### Blaze Compiler — Automatic Performance

The Blaze compiler is a build-time optimization layer that pre-renders static portions of your Blade templates through "code folding." It makes Blade components render up to **20x faster** with zero code changes from you.

This runs automatically in Livewire 4 — no configuration needed. Static HTML that never changes is compiled once and served directly, while dynamic portions are still evaluated at runtime.

---

## When to Use Livewire vs Alpine.js

| Scenario | Use |
|----------|-----|
| Form submission / validation | Livewire |
| Loading data from DB or file | Livewire `mount()` |
| CRUD actions | Livewire |
| UI toggles (open/close, tabs) | Alpine.js |
| Animations, transitions | Alpine.js |
| Reading from parent Livewire state | Alpine.js `$wire` bridge |

---

## Best Practices

1. **Type-hint `mount()` arguments** — `public function mount(int $id, string $slug): void`
2. **Use `wire:key`** on all looped elements to help Livewire diff correctly (v4 defaults `smart_wire_keys` to `true`, but explicit keys remain best practice)
3. **Debounce `wire:model.live`** for search/filter inputs to reduce round trips
4. **Use Blade comments `{{-- --}}`** instead of HTML comments inside Blade files
5. **Use `#[Computed]`** for derived values instead of recalculating in multiple places
6. **Keep server logic out of Alpine.js** — Alpine is view layer only
7. **Responsive classes** — Tailwind mobile-first: `text-sm md:text-base lg:text-lg`
8. **Accessibility** — include `aria-` attributes and semantic HTML tags
9. **Use `data-loading:` Tailwind variants** for loading states instead of complex `wire:loading` setups
10. **Use Islands for expensive sections** — wrap heavy components in `@island(lazy: true)` to avoid blocking initial render
11. **Leverage scoped styles** — keep component CSS inside the `<style>` block rather than global stylesheets
12. **Use PHP 8.4 property hooks** — replace `updated*` lifecycle methods with native getters/setters where possible
13. **Use `Route::livewire()`** for page components instead of `Route::get()`

---

## Migration Checklist

- [ ] Identify if component needs server state (use Livewire) or UI-only state (use Alpine.js)
- [ ] Create single-file component with `new class extends Component {}` in a `⚡name.blade.php` file
- [ ] Replace `useState` with typed public properties on the component class
- [ ] Convert `useEffect(fn, [])` to `public function mount(): void { ... }`
- [ ] Convert `useEffect(fn, [dep])` to `updatedPropertyName()` method or PHP 8.4 property hooks
- [ ] Replace `useMemo` with `#[Computed]` methods, reference as `$this->methodName`
- [ ] Replace `onClick` handlers with `wire:click="methodName(...)"`
- [ ] Replace controlled inputs with `wire:model` (add `.live.debounce.300ms` for search)
- [ ] Replace `fetch()` with PHP data loading in `mount()`
- [ ] Replace `className` with `class`
- [ ] Replace `{condition && <X />}` with `@if` / `@endif`
- [ ] Replace `.map()` with `@foreach` and add `wire:key`
- [ ] Replace React Router `<Link>` with `<a href="{{ route('name') }}">`
- [ ] Wrap route param loading in `mount(int $id)` with type-hinted parameters
- [ ] Configure layout in `config/livewire.php` or use `#[Layout('layouts::app')]`
- [ ] Register routes with `Route::livewire()` for page components
- [ ] Wrap expensive sections in `@island(lazy: true)` for performance
- [ ] Replace loading state logic with `data-loading:` Tailwind variants
- [ ] Move component-specific CSS into `<style>` blocks for automatic scoping
- [ ] Test with Livewire dev tools in browser
- [ ] Verify Alpine.js interactions do not conflict with `wire:model`

